</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Fortiborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fortiborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Fortiborus</taxonomicName>
Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010a: 17.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Phloeosinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phloeosinus major" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phloeosinus major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stebbing, 1909; original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Fortiborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fortiborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fortiborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are among the largest xyleborines in Southeast Asia (4.8-6.6 mm and 2.52-3.06
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide). 
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Fortiborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fortiborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fortiborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the robust pronotum; declivity flattened and broadened laterally, apex angulate; anterior edge of pronotum extended anteriad, bearing a distinct row of serrations; antennal club distinctly pubescent, type 4; eyes very large, deeply emarginate; scutellum flat, flush with elytra; procoxae contiguous; and mycangial tufts absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Fortiborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fortiborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fortiborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to some large 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Euwallacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Euwallacea" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Euwallacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species except the margin of segment 1 of antennal club is concave and recurved; anterior edge of pronotum produced anteriad, bearing row of serrations; and protibiae rounded, with seven or more denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="similar genera">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Similar genera.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Euwallacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Euwallacea" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Euwallacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eichhoff" authorityYear="1864" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Stereocaulaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xyleborus" order="Lecanorales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Found throughout Southeast Asia and Oceania.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="gallery system">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gallery system.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The galleries are regularly branched in one transverse plane and are without brood chambers (
<bibRefCitation author="Browne, FG" journalOrPublisher="Malayan Forest Records" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 255" refId="B70" refString="Browne, FG, 1961b. The biology of Malayan Scolytidae and Platypodidae. Malayan Forest Records 22: 1 - 255" title="The biology of Malayan Scolytidae and Platypodidae." volume="22" year="1961 b">Browne 1961b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species of this genus are all closely associated with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eichhoff" authorityYear="1864" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Dipterocarpaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Lecanorales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="family">Dipterocarpaceae</taxonomicName>
and are not definitely known to breed in other families of trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
